## Proposed Canonical TranscriptEntry Schema (from research)

```
TranscriptEntry {
  id:           UUID
  timestamp:    ISO 8601
  session_id:   UUID          // A2A ContextID
  task_id:      UUID?         // A2A TaskID / ACP RunId
  role:         "user"|"assistant"|"tool"|"system"
  content:      ContentPart[]
  tool_use?: {
    id:         string
    name:       string        // MCP tool name
    input:      object
  }
  tool_result?: {
    tool_use_id: string
    content:     ContentPart[]
    is_error:    bool
  }
  reasoning?:   string        // ACP TrajectoryMetadata.message
  references:   UUID[]        // A2A referenceTaskIds
  metadata:     map[string, any]
  source: {
    harness:    string        // "claude-code", "opencode", etc.
    model:      string?       // models.dev canonical ID
    protocol:   "mcp"|"a2a"|"raw"
  }
}

ContentPart (discriminated union via "type"):
  { type:"text", text, mime_type? }
  { type:"file", data? (base64), uri?, mime_type, filename? }
  { type:"data", data: object, mime_type? }
  { type:"resource_link", uri, name?, mime_type? }
```

Phase 1 research complete. Ready for Phase 2 (URE/URD).

REVIEWER-C (Elegance) findings:

MINOR-1: _import_aura_release() called per-test instead of via a session-scoped fixture.

Location: tests/test_aura_release.py — all four test methods call _import_aura_release() independently.

Each call re-executes the entire module body via spec.loader.exec_module(mod) and overwrites sys.modules['aura_release'] with a freshly executed module object. While functionally correct for the current test suite, this is subtler than necessary: the module has no mutable module-level state that needs resetting between tests, so there is no defensive benefit from re-importing per test. A session-scoped pytest fixture returning the module once would make the intent explicit ('we import once, exercise multiple behaviours') and remove the silent sys.modules overwrite on each invocation.

Suggested direction: extract a session-scoped fixture:

    @pytest.fixture(scope='session')
    def aura_release():
        return _import_aura_release()

and replace the four inline calls with the fixture parameter. No coverage is lost; the four test cases still exercise all four code paths.

Severity: MINOR — no test correctness issue today, purely an elegance and intent-clarity concern.
